A tutorial for computing W for the SEIR model

Author

Dylan Morris

Published

July 11, 2023

Introduction

This notebook provides a step-by-step guide for working with RandomTimeShifts.jl. This involves how functions needed to estimate the moments (Section 3), estimate the LST using the PE method, and sample realisations of W using the M3 method (Section 3.5) can be defined. To start with make sure the package is installed and we have access to itâs functions.

if Base.find_package("RandomTimeShifts") === nothing 
    using Pkg
    Pkg.add(url = "https://github.com/djmorris7/RandomTimeShifts.jl")
end
import RandomTimeShifts as rts
using OrdinaryDiffEq
using Random
using Distributions
using CairoMakie

Model specification

Weâll work with the SEIR model as specified in Section 4.1 of the paper, with parameters given by (\beta, \sigma, \gamma) = (0.56, 0.5, 0.33). For this example weâll consider a population of size N = 10^6 and assume the trivial initial condition of the branching process (BP) approximation as \boldsymbol{Z}(0) = (1, 0). The progeny generating functions are given by,

f_1(\boldsymbol{s}) = s_2 ,\quad f_2(\boldsymbol{s}) = \frac{\gamma + \beta s_1 s_2}{\gamma + \beta}

and the lifetimes of individuals are specified by the vector,

\boldsymbol{a} = (\sigma, \gamma + \beta).

From the progeny generating functions we can specify the matrix \Omega:

\Omega = \begin{pmatrix} -\sigma & \sigma \\ \beta & -\gamma \end{pmatrix}.

In code we can detail these components as follows:

Z0 = [1, 0]
pars = (0.56, 0.5, 0.33)
Î², Ï, Î³ = pars
Î© = [-Ï Ï
     Î² -Î³]

Î»1, u_norm, v_norm = rts.calculate_BP_contributions(Î©)
lifetimes = [Ï, Î² + Î³]

PE method

Differentiating the functional equations

The progeny generating function for individuals of type 1 is f_1(\boldsymbol{s}) = s_2 and hence, as we have linear dynamics, we utilise the diff_linear() function. For example, if we wanted the system for the second moment (n_deriv = 2) we would run:

n_deriv = 2
become_type = 2
total_types = 2
coeffs_linear, C1 = rts.diff_linear(lifetimes[1], n_deriv, Î»1, become_type, total_types)

We then add the contributions of differentiating the lefthand side (Section 3.3.1) of the functional equation to the coeffs arrays returned from each function:

coeffs_linear += rts.lhs_coeffs(1; num_phis = 2)
println("coeffs = $(round.(coeffs_linear, digits = 3)), constant = $C1")
coeffs = [1.0, -0.674], constant = 0.0

This result gives us the linear equation

E[W_1^2] - 0.674 E[W_2^2] = 0.

The process is much the same for individuals of type 2 except that we have quadratic branching dynamics and can use the diff_quadratic() function making sure to specify what the moment generating functions, \xi_i, are that would appear in this function. A simple way of determining this is look at the index of the progeny generating function (which is a 2) and the indices of the s_i (1 and 2) and so we supply phi_idxs = [2, 1, 2] to diff_quadratic(). Thereâs an additional point to note here that we need to supply the previous moments as well in the calculation as shown in Section 3.3.3 so we can appropriately get the constant term.

phi_idxs = [2, 1, 2]
coeffs_quadratic, C2 = rts.diff_quadratic(Î², lifetimes[2], n_derivs, Î», prev_moments, phi_idxs)

Again, we add the contributions of differentiating the lefthand side (Section 3.3.1) of the functional equation to the coeffs arrays returned from each function:

coeffs_quadratic += rts.lhs_coeffs(2; num_phis = 2)

We can simply construct the linear system and the full code is as follows:

function diff_SEIR_coeffs!(A, b, Î², lifetimes, Î», phis)
    n_previous, num_phis = size(phis)
    n = n_previous + 1

    coeffs_linear, C1 = rts.diff_linear(lifetimes[1], n, Î», 2, 2)
    coeffs_quadratic, C2 = rts.diff_quadratic(Î², lifetimes[2], n, Î», phis, [2, 1, 2])

    coeffs_linear += rts.lhs_coeffs(1; num_phis = 2)
    coeffs_quadratic += rts.lhs_coeffs(2; num_phis = 2)

    A[1, :] .= coeffs_linear
    A[2, :] .= coeffs_quadratic
    b[1] = C1
    b[2] = C2

    return nothing
end
diff_SEIR_coeffs! (generic function with 1 method)

A simple optimisation here that weâre using which enables reuse of arrays is to specify the updates in-place.

Calculating the moments

We can automate this process using diff_SEIR_coeffs!() to construct the linear system A\boldsymbol{x} = \boldsymbol{b} where \boldsymbol{x} = (E[W_1^2], E[W_1^2])^{T} and if we wanted the first 2 moments, then:

num_pgfs = 2
# Create a matrix for the phis ensures correct orientation
phis = zeros(Float64, 1, 2)
# The first moments of W are determined by u
phis[1, :] .= u_norm

# Initialise arrays to reuse for computations
A = zeros(Float64, num_pgfs, num_pgfs)
b = zeros(Float64, num_pgfs)

# Differentiate the functional equations a single time
diff_SEIR_coeffs!(A, b, Î², lifetimes, Î»1, phis)

The matrix, A, is given by,

round.(A, digits = 3)
2Ã2 Matrix{Float64}:
  1.0    -0.674
 -0.495   0.505

and the constant vector, \boldsymbol{b}, is

round.(b, digits = 3)
2-element Vector{Float64}:
 0.0
 0.244

To get the second moments we solve A\boldsymbol{x} = \boldsymbol{b},

second_moments = round.(A \ b, digits = 3)
2-element Vector{Float64}:
 0.959
 1.423

In other words, E[W_1^2] = 0.959 and E[W_2^2] = 1.423.

We can setup a function to calculate the moments recursively. We do this by assuming that the parameters pars are already defined.

Î², Ï, Î³ = pars
Î© = [-Ï Ï
     Î² -Î³]

Î»1, u_norm, v_norm = rts.calculate_BP_contributions(Î©)
lifetimes = [Ï, Î² + Î³]

Then we pass this to a function and we could calculate an arbitrary number of moments (here num_moments = 3):

num_moments = 3
moments = rts.calculate_moments_ND(diff_SEIR_coeffs_!, num_moments, Î©)

LSTs, inverse LSTs, and distributions

Computing the LST

Using the previous section we can now compute the LST. Doing this involves three parts:

  1. Estimate \lambda, \boldsymbol{u} and \boldsymbol{v} for the BP model,
  2. Then using the functions defined above, calculate the moments and the error bound
  3. Setup the system of ODEâs governing the neighbourhood extension part.

Following these, we simply call rts.construct_lst() to compute the estimate to the LST. The only extra part we need is a function for solving for \boldsymbol{F}(\boldsymbol{s}, t) at a fixed value of \boldsymbol{s}:

function F_fixed_s!(du, u, pars, t)
    Î², Ï, Î³ = pars
    du[1] = -Ï * u[1] + Ï * u[2]
    du[2] = Î³ - (Î² + Î³) * u[2] + Î² * u[1] * u[2]
    return nothing
end
F_fixed_s! (generic function with 1 method)

Now we can easily calculate the LST. Note that this can be simplified but weâve left it a little more terse to explicitly demonstrate each step.

function construct_lst(pars, Z0, num_moments; Ïµ = 1e-6, h = 2.0)
    # 1. Calculate quantities from the branching process
    Î², Ï, Î³ = pars
    Î© = [-Ï Ï
         Î² -Î³]

    Î»1, u_norm, v_norm = rts.calculate_BP_contributions(Î©)
    EW = sum(Z0 .* u_norm)

    # 2. Calculate the moments and error bounds
    diff_SEIR_coeffs_!(A, b, phis) = diff_SEIR_coeffs!(A, b, Î², lifetimes, Î»1, phis)
    moments = rts.calculate_moments_ND(diff_SEIR_coeffs_!, num_moments, Î©)
    error_moment = moments[end, :]
    moments = moments[begin:(end - 1), :]
    coeffs = rts.moment_coeffs(moments)
    L = rts.error_bounds(Ïµ, error_moment, num_moments)

    # 3. Setup the system to extend the neighbourhood
    prob = ODEProblem(F_fixed_s!, zeros(length(Z0)), (0, h), pars,
                      save_start = false, saveat = h)
    F_offspring(s) = rts.F_offspring_ode(s, prob)
    Î¼ = exp(h * Î»1)

    # Construct the LST
    lst_w = rts.construct_lst(coeffs, Î¼, F_offspring, L, Z0, Î»1, h)
    
    return lst_w 
end

Distributions from the LST

To invert the LST we need to estimate the extinction probability from the BP model. This can be done by defining a function.

function calculate_extinction_probs(pars)
    q0 = [0, 0]
    tspan = (0, 10000)

    prob = ODEProblem(F_fixed_s!, q0, tspan, pars)
    sol = solve(prob,
                Tsit5();
                save_start = false,
                save_everystep = false,
                save_end = true,
                abstol = 1e-9,
                reltol = 1e-9)

    q1 = sol.u[1]

    return q1
end
calculate_extinction_probs (generic function with 1 method)

Note that solving the differential equations is equivalent to finding the minimal non negative solution of the equation \boldsymbol{f}(\boldsymbol{q}) = \boldsymbol{q}.

Next we simply apply the inversion method from the package.

function invert_lst(Z0, pars, lst)
    q1 = calculate_extinction_probs(pars)
    q_star = prod(q1 .^ Z0)
    W_cdf = rts.construct_W_cdf_ilst(lst, q_star)
    
    return W_cdf
end
invert_lst (generic function with 2 methods)

With the distribution of W in hand we can readily estimate the distribution and hence the density of the time-shift conditional on W > 0.

function time_shift_from_W_cdf(t_range, W_cdf, EW, Î»1)
    q_star = W_cdf(0.0)

    F_Ï_cdf(t) = W_cdf_ilst(exp(Î»1 * t) * EW)
    cdf_vals = rts.eval_cdf(F_Ï_cdf, t_range)
    pdf_vals = rts.pdf_from_cdf(cdf_vals, Ît) ./ (1 - q_star)
    # We need to remove off the jump in the CDF and then renormalise
    # Think about this at the limits x -> 0 and x -> â of 
    # (F(x) - q_star) / (1 - q_star) and it makes sense.
    cdf_vals = (cdf_vals .- q_star) ./ (1 - q_star)

    return pdf_vals, cdf_vals
end
time_shift_from_W_cdf (generic function with 1 method)
W_cdf = invert_lst([1, 0], pars, lst)

Moment matching

The moment matching method uses much of the same setup code as we needed for the PE method.

We begin by calculating the first five moments of W and the extinction probabilities:

# 1. Calculate quantities from the branching process
Î², Ï, Î³ = pars
Î© = [-Ï Ï
        Î² -Î³]

Î»1, u_norm, v_norm = rts.calculate_BP_contributions(Î©)
EW = sum(Z0 .* u_norm)

# 2. Calculate the moments and error bounds
diff_SEIR_coeffs_!(A, b, phis) = diff_SEIR_coeffs!(A, b, Î², lifetimes, Î»1, phis)

num_moments = 5
moments = rts.calculate_moments_ND(diff_SEIR_coeffs_!, num_moments, Î©)
q1 = calculate_extinction_probs(pars)
2-element Vector{Float64}:
 0.5892857140821364
 0.5892857144637667

Now we optimise the loss function to get the parameters of the surrogate distribution for W | W > 0.

# Estimate the distribution of timeshifts through m3 method
pars_m3 = rts.minimise_loss(moments, q1)
2-element Vector{Vector{Float64}}:
 [1.0665141093030468, 1.0196144471992665, 1.0008676277942428]
 [1.4823632437564649, 1.018792827278239, 1.0880411705287052]

This gives W_1 | W_1 > 0 \sim GG(1.067, 1.020, 1.001) and W_2 | W_2 > 0 \sim GG(1.482, 1.019, 1.088).

Now we can sample realisations and look at the distribution:

W_samples = rts.sample_W(10000, pars_m3, q1, Z0)

fig, ax = hist(W_samples, normalization = :probability, )
ax.xlabel = "w"
ax.ylabel = "density"
fig

Consistency between methods

For a sanity check we can compare (visually) the distributions obtained using the two methods. The easiest way to do this is through the CDF and we renormalise it to remove the point mass at W = 0.

W_samples = rts.sample_W(10000, pars_m3, q1, Z0)

w_range = 0:0.5:maximum(W_samples)
cdf_vals = rts.eval_cdf(W_cdf, w_range)
cdf_vals = (cdf_vals .- W_cdf(0)) ./ (1 - W_cdf(0))

fig, ax = ecdfplot(W_samples, color = "red")
scatter!(ax, w_range, cdf_vals)
ax.xlabel = "w"
ax.ylabel = "density"
fig

We see great consistency between the two methods and so things are working as we expect.

# Introduction 

This notebook provides a step-by-step guide for working with `RandomTimeShifts.jl`. 
This involves how functions needed to estimate the moments (Section 3), estimate the LST using the PE method, and sample realisations of $W$ using the M3 method (Section 3.5) can be defined. 
To start with make sure the package is installed and we have access to it's functions. 


## Model specification

We'll work with the SEIR model as specified in Section 4.1 of the paper, with parameters given by $(\beta, \sigma, \gamma) = (0.56, 0.5, 0.33)$.
For this example we'll consider a population of size $N = 10^6$ and assume the trivial initial condition of the branching process (BP) approximation as $\boldsymbol{Z}(0) = (1, 0)$.
The progeny generating functions are given by,

$$
f_1(\boldsymbol{s}) = s_2 ,\quad f_2(\boldsymbol{s}) = \frac{\gamma + \beta s_1 s_2}{\gamma + \beta}
$$

and the lifetimes of individuals are specified by the vector, 

$$
\boldsymbol{a} = (\sigma, \gamma + \beta).
$$

From the progeny generating functions we can specify the matrix $\Omega$: 

$$
\Omega = \begin{pmatrix}
  -\sigma & \sigma \\

\end{pmatrix}.

# PE method 

## Differentiating the functional equations

The progeny generating function for individuals of type 1 is $f_1(\boldsymbol{s}) = s_2$ and hence, as we have linear dynamics, we utilise the `diff_linear()` function. 
For example, if we wanted the system for the second moment (`n_deriv = 2`) we would run:

```{julia}
#| output: false
n_deriv = 2
become_type = 2
total_types = 2
coeffs_linear, C1 = rts.diff_linear(lifetimes[1], n_deriv, Î»1, become_type, total_types)
```

We then add the contributions of differentiating the lefthand side (Section 3.3.1) of the functional equation to the coeffs arrays returned from each function:

```{julia}
coeffs_linear += rts.lhs_coeffs(1; num_phis = 2)
println("coeffs = $(round.(coeffs_linear, digits = 3)), constant = $C1")
```

This result gives us the linear equation

$$
E[W_1^2] - 0.674 E[W_2^2] = 0.
$$

The process is much the same for individuals of type 2 except that we have quadratic branching dynamics and can use the `diff_quadratic()` function making sure to specify what the moment generating functions, $\xi_i$, are that would appear in this function. 
A simple way of determining this is look at the index of the progeny generating function (which is a 2) and the indices of the $s_i$ (1 and 2) and so we supply `phi_idxs = [2, 1, 2]` to `diff_quadratic()`.
There's an additional point to note here that we need to supply the previous moments as well in the calculation as shown in Section 3.3.3 so we can appropriately get the constant term. 

```{julia}
#| eval: false
phi_idxs = [2, 1, 2]
coeffs_quadratic, C2 = rts.diff_quadratic(Î², lifetimes[2], n_derivs, Î», prev_moments, phi_idxs)
```

Again, we add the contributions of differentiating the lefthand side (Section 3.3.1) of the functional equation to the coeffs arrays returned from each function:

```{julia}
#| eval: false
coeffs_quadratic += rts.lhs_coeffs(2; num_phis = 2)
```

We can simply construct the linear system and the full code is as follows:

```{julia}
function diff_SEIR_coeffs!(A, b, Î², lifetimes, Î», phis)
    n_previous, num_phis = size(phis)
    n = n_previous + 1

    coeffs_linear, C1 = rts.diff_linear(lifetimes[1], n, Î», 2, 2)
    coeffs_quadratic, C2 = rts.diff_quadratic(Î², lifetimes[2], n, Î», phis, [2, 1, 2])

    coeffs_linear += rts.lhs_coeffs(1; num_phis = 2)
    coeffs_quadratic += rts.lhs_coeffs(2; num_phis = 2)

    A[1, :] .= coeffs_linear
    A[2, :] .= coeffs_quadratic
    b[1] = C1
    b[2] = C2

    return nothing
end
```

A simple optimisation here that we're using which enables reuse of arrays is to specify the updates in-place.

## LSTs, inverse LSTs, and distributions 

### Computing the LST

Using the previous section we can now compute the LST. 
Doing this involves three parts: 

1. Estimate $\lambda$, $\boldsymbol{u}$ and $\boldsymbol{v}$ for the BP model, 
2. Then using the functions defined above, calculate the moments and the error bound
3. Setup the system of ODE's governing the neighbourhood extension part.

Following these, we simply call `rts.construct_lst()` to compute the estimate to the LST. 
The only extra part we need is a function for solving for $\boldsymbol{F}(\boldsymbol{s}, t)$ at a fixed value of $\boldsymbol{s}$:

```{julia}
function F_fixed_s!(du, u, pars, t)
    Î², Ï, Î³ = pars
    du[1] = -Ï * u[1] + Ï * u[2]
    du[2] = Î³ - (Î² + Î³) * u[2] + Î² * u[1] * u[2]
    return nothing
end
```

Now we can easily calculate the LST. 
Note that this can be simplified but we've left it a little more terse to explicitly demonstrate each step. 

```{julia}

    Î², Ï, Î³ = pars
    Î© = [-Ï Ï
         Î² -Î³]

    moments = rts.calculate_moments_ND(diff_SEIR_coeffs_!, num_moments, Î©)
    error_moment = moments[end, :]
    moments = moments[begin:(end - 1), :]
    coeffs = rts.moment_coeffs(moments)
    L = rts.error_bounds(Ïµ, error_moment, num_moments)

    # 3. Setup the system to extend the neighbourhood
    prob = ODEProblem(F_fixed_s!, zeros(length(Z0)), (0, h), pars,
                      save_start = false, saveat = h)
    F_offspring(s) = rts.F_offspring_ode(s, prob)
    Î¼ = exp(h * Î»1)

    # Construct the LST
    lst_w = rts.construct_lst(coeffs, Î¼, F_offspring, L, Z0, Î»1, h)
    
    return lst_w 
end
```

We can the easily construct a function handle for the lst (where `num_moments` and `h` are chosen as in the paper): 

```{julia}
num_moments = 30
lst = construct_lst(pars, Z0, num_moments)
```

which can be evaluated easily `lst(0.8)` 

```{julia}
lst(0.8)
```

or for vectors (using Julia's dot syntax) as 

```{julia}
x = rand.(Uniform(0, 10), 5)
lst.(x)
```

### Distributions from the LST
 
To invert the LST we need to estimate the extinction probability from the BP model. This can be done by defining a function.

```{julia}
function calculate_extinction_probs(pars)
    q0 = [0, 0]
    tspan = (0, 10000)

    prob = ODEProblem(F_fixed_s!, q0, tspan, pars)
    sol = solve(prob,
                Tsit5();
                save_start = false,
                save_everystep = false,
                save_end = true,
                abstol = 1e-9,
                reltol = 1e-9)

    q1 = sol.u[1]

    return q1
end
```

Note that solving the differential equations is equivalent to finding the minimal non negative solution of the equation $\boldsymbol{f}(\boldsymbol{q}) = \boldsymbol{q}$. 
 
Next we simply apply the inversion method from the package. 
 
```{julia}
function invert_lst(Z0, pars, lst)
    q1 = calculate_extinction_probs(pars)
    q_star = prod(q1 .^ Z0)
    W_cdf = rts.construct_W_cdf_ilst(lst, q_star)
    
    return W_cdf
end
```

With the distribution of $W$ in hand we can readily estimate the distribution and hence the density of the time-shift conditional on $W > 0$. 

```{julia}
function time_shift_from_W_cdf(t_range, W_cdf, EW, Î»1)
    q_star = W_cdf(0.0)

    F_Ï_cdf(t) = W_cdf_ilst(exp(Î»1 * t) * EW)
    cdf_vals = rts.eval_cdf(F_Ï_cdf, t_range)
    pdf_vals = rts.pdf_from_cdf(cdf_vals, Ît) ./ (1 - q_star)
    # We need to remove off the jump in the CDF and then renormalise
    # Think about this at the limits x -> 0 and x -> â of 
    # (F(x) - q_star) / (1 - q_star) and it makes sense.
    cdf_vals = (cdf_vals .- q_star) ./ (1 - q_star)

    return pdf_vals, cdf_vals
end
```

```{julia}
W_cdf = invert_lst([1, 0], pars, lst)
```

# Moment matching 

The moment matching method uses much of the same setup code as we needed for the PE method. 

We begin by calculating the first five moments of $W$ and the extinction probabilities:

```{julia}
# 1. Calculate quantities from the branching process
Î², Ï, Î³ = pars
Î© = [-Ï Ï
        Î² -Î³]

Î»1, u_norm, v_norm = rts.calculate_BP_contributions(Î©)
EW = sum(Z0 .* u_norm)

# 2. Calculate the moments and error bounds
diff_SEIR_coeffs_!(A, b, phis) = diff_SEIR_coeffs!(A, b, Î², lifetimes, Î»1, phis)

num_moments = 5
moments = rts.calculate_moments_ND(diff_SEIR_coeffs_!, num_moments, Î©)
q1 = calculate_extinction_probs(pars)
```

Now we optimise the loss function to get the parameters of the surrogate distribution for $W | W > 0$.

```{julia}
# Estimate the distribution of timeshifts through m3 method
pars_m3 = rts.minimise_loss(moments, q1)
```

This gives $W_1 | W_1 > 0 \sim GG(1.067, 1.020, 1.001)$ and $W_2 | W_2 > 0 \sim GG(1.482, 1.019, 1.088)$.

Now we can sample realisations and look at the distribution:

```{julia}
W_samples = rts.sample_W(10000, pars_m3, q1, Z0)

fig, ax = hist(W_samples, normalization = :probability, )
ax.xlabel = "w"
ax.ylabel = "density"
fig
```

# Consistency between methods

For a sanity check we can compare (visually) the distributions obtained using the two methods. 
The easiest way to do this is through the CDF and we renormalise it to remove the point mass at $W = 0$.

```{julia}
W_samples = rts.sample_W(10000, pars_m3, q1, Z0)

w_range = 0:0.5:maximum(W_samples)
cdf_vals = rts.eval_cdf(W_cdf, w_range)
cdf_vals = (cdf_vals .- W_cdf(0)) ./ (1 - W_cdf(0))

fig, ax = ecdfplot(W_samples, color = "red")
scatter!(ax, w_range, cdf_vals)
ax.xlabel = "w"
ax.ylabel = "density"
fig
```

We see great consistency between the two methods and so things are working as we expect.
